PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F412A1781700487
OL,3,CComplainants in Donaldson case 'not
OL,4,Creliable enough' for guilty verdict-
OL,5,C defence
OL,7,FOn Wednesday, Mr Vaughan continued his
OL,8,Fclosing speech, by dealing with
OL,9,Fallegations made by Complainant A
OL,10,Fagainst Donaldson.
OL,12,FHe described an incident where A
OL,13,Falleged Donaldson had used a light to
OL,14,Fstare at her private parts as a
OL,15,F"misunderstanding".
OL,17,FHe said: "She has proven herself to be
OL,18,Fa very, very unreliable witness."
OL,26,@wD@AOUwD@RO]yD@JOUzD@aO]
OL,1,W~k4 jw=hw1 hw}h7}j7}            G4/8
OL,2,W/*% /*%/"-$+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNI NewsCClean Feed FThis Day
FL,413,410,140,120,000,100
PN,41205
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F412A1781700487
OL,3,CComplainants in Donaldson case 'not
OL,4,Creliable enough' for guilty verdict-
OL,5,C defence
OL,7,FMr Vaughan pointed out that
OL,8,FComplainant A had stated her memories
OL,9,Fof the incident were "foggy".
OL,11,FHe said: "She is not sure about the
OL,12,Fvery thing the prosecution invite you
OL,13,Fto be sure about."
OL,15,FThe barrister said: "We say the
OL,16,Fevidence shows that nothing happened."
OL,18,FMr Vaughan said a separate allegation
OL,19,Fthat Donaldson had touched her lacks
OL,20,F"any semblance of credibility".
OL,26,@qD@VOUqD@\O]sD@JOUuD@RO]wD@UOUxD@fO]|D@
OL,26,AAOU|D@^O]
OL,1,W~k4 jw=hw1 hw}h7}j7}            G5/8
OL,2,W/*% /*%/"-$+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
